The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, August 28, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Punjab National Bank has decided to delist its shares from the Delhi Stock Exchange due to poor trading on the bourse in recent years. The shareholders approval had been obtained at an annual general body meeting of the bank held on July 3, 2004, the bank said. 																								 Navi Mumbai-based pharma player Pearl Organics said its merger with Wander Pvt Ltd has been cleared by the Mumbai high court with a 4:1 swap ratio. The merger of the two companies, effective October 1, 2003, would lead to the formation of a consolidated entity, Wanbury Ltd.																								 Indian Oil Corporations Barauni refinery and Bongaigaon Refineries and Petrochemicals Ltd received the second and third prize, respectively, for their safety record in 2002-03, while Hindustan Petroleums Mumbai refinery was placed first. IBP won the safety award in the oil marketing segment, while Bharat Petroleum was placed first in the LPG section.																								 IBP, an Indian Oil group company, has signed a memorandum of collaboration with Petronet LNG for transporting LNG being imported at Dahej in Gujarat in specialised cryogenic bullet trucks to small industrial consumers not situated on major gas pipeline routes.																								 Bajaj Capital, the financial planning and investment advisory services company, hopes to mobilise Rs 500 crore for the 9 per cent senior citizen scheme, launched by the government earlier this month. The company would mobilise the sum through its network of 90 branches across 40 cities.																								 Sankranthi Agarbathi Co, a Bangalore-based incense stick manufacturer, has obtained the ISO 9001:2000 certificate for best manufacturing practices. ADVERTISEMENT
